A girth, sometimes called a cinch (Western riding), is a piece of equipment used to keep the [MASK] in place on a horse or other animal.
It passes under the barrel of the equine, usually attached to the [MASK] on both sides by two or three leather straps called billets.

Girths are used on Australian and English saddles, while western saddles and many pack saddles have a cinch, which is fastened to the [MASK] by a single wide leather strap on each side, called a latigo.

Although a girth is often enough to keep a well-fitting [MASK] in place, other pieces of equipment are also used in jumping or speed sports such as polo, eventing, show jumping, and fox hunting; or on rough terrain such as trail riding, These include breastplates, overgirths, cruppers, and, on pack saddles, breeching.
